content/uploads/2023/09/Jann-Wenner@2000x1270-1392x884.jpg 1392w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/Jann-Wenner@2000x1270-1068x678.jpg 1068w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px" /></p><p> <em>《滚石》</em>杂志在其创始人 Jann Wenner 最近发表有争议的言论后发表了一份声明。</p><p> <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/jann-wenner-says-female-and-black-artists-not-intellectual-enough-to-be-interviewed-for-his-new-book-3498935">上周，这位创始人</a>在接受他的新书<em>《大师》</em>采访时，与七位“摇滚哲学家”进行了讨论，而这些人都是白人男性，因此遭到了一波强烈反对。</p><p>其中包括<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/bono">波诺</a>、<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/bob-dylan">鲍勃·迪伦</a>、已故的杰里·加西亚、<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/mick-jagger">米克·贾格尔、</a>已故的<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/john-lennon">约翰·列侬</a>、<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/bruce-springsteen">布鲁斯·斯普林斯汀</a>和<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/pete-townshend">皮特·汤森德</a>，温纳在接受<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/international/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>《纽约时报》</em></a>大卫·马尔凯斯采访时表示：</p><p> “<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/Joni-mitchell">乔尼（米切尔）</a>不是一位摇滚哲学家。在我看来，她没有通过那个测试。不是通过她的作品，也不是通过她所做的其他采访。我采访的人都是摇滚哲学家。”</p><p>他继续说道：“黑人艺术家——你知道，<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/stevie-wonder">史蒂夫·旺德</a>，天才，对吧？ I suppose when you use a word as broad as &#39;masters&#39;, the fault is using that word. Maybe <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/marvin-gaye">Marvin Gaye</a> or <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/curtis-mayfield">Curtis Mayfield</a> ? I mean, they just didn&#39;t articulate at that level.” </p><figure id="attachment_3498936" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-3498936" style="width: 2000px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-3498936" src="https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1.jpg" alt="简·温纳" width="2000" height="1270" srcset="https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1.jpg 2000w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1-400x254.jpg 400w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1-800x508.jpg 800w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1-696x442.jpg 696w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1-1392x884.jpg 1392w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/jann-wennerbruce-glikas-1-1068x678.jpg 1068w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-3498936" class="wp-caption-text"> Jann Wenner. Credit: Bruce Glikas/Getty</figcaption></figure><p> The comments soon sparked widespread criticism and led to Wenner&#39;s <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/jann-wenner-removed-from-rock-roll-hall-of-fame-board-after-controversial-interview-3499229">removal from the board of the Rock &amp; Roll Hall Of Fame</a> , which he co-founded.</p><p> Now, <em>Rolling Stone,</em> which Wenner stopped working for in 2019, has issued a public statement following the comments. It also confirmed that his personal views do not reflect those of the company.</p><p> “Jann Wenner&#39;s recent statements to the <em>New York Times</em> do not represent the values and practices of today&#39;s <em>Rolling Stone</em> ,” the statement on X read.</p><p> “Jann Wenner has not been directly involved in our operations since 2019. Our purpose, especially since his departure, has been to tell stories that reflect the diversity of voices and experiences that shape our world,” it added. “At <em>Rolling Stone</em> ’s core is the understanding that music above all can bring us together, not divide us.”</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-width="550" data-dnt="true"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"> Our statement on Jann Wenner&#39;s recent comments. <a href="https://t.co/dL7lMSTP3k">pic.twitter.com/dL7lMSTP3k</a></p><p> — Rolling Stone (@RollingStone) <a href="https://twitter.com/RollingStone/status/1703816783516365022?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">September 18, 2023</a> </p></blockquote><p><script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><p> Following his removal from the Rock &amp; Roll Hall Of Fame, it was also reported that Wenner issued an apology for his comments during the interview with Marchese.</p><p> “In my interview with <em>The New York Times</em> I made comments that diminished the contributions, genius and impact of Black and women artists and I apologise wholeheartedly for those remarks,” he said.</p><p> “ <em>The Masters</em> is a collection of interviews I&#39;ve done over the years that seemed to me to best represent an idea of rock&#39;n&#39;roll&#39;s impact on my world; they were not meant to represent the whole of music and its diverse and important originators but to reflect the high points of my career and interviews I felt illustrated the breadth and experience in that career.”</p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/rolling-stone-shares-statement-controversy-founder-jann-wenner-3500274">Rolling Stone shares statement following controversy around founder, Jann Wenner</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.nme.com">NME</a> .</p> ;
